body:
@NathanSweet I'm having some problems with calling InputMultiplexer.clear() and I think this fix is what messes it up because when I set the input as handled in my inputProcessor and return true, the processors.end() is never called and the _iterating_ field in the DelayedRemovalArray just keeps increasing in every key:
```
processors.begin();
for (int i = 0, n = processors.size; i < n; i++)
if (processors.get(i).keyDown(keycode)) return true;
processors.end();
```
We could add processors.end() before returning true here, but  if @PokeMMO in his example handled the input and  added return true after 
```
multiplexer.removeProcessor(processor1);
```
the multiplexer would remove the processor and break the loop anyway, right?

This, but I'm also not sure if this fix was needed at all, because in @PokeMMO 's example if he had handled the input by returning true, the loop of the processors would break and it would not cause an exception. Unless there is a use case that he shouldn't return true.

Like this:
```
@Override
public boolean keyDown (int keycode) {
	if(this == processor1) {
		multiplexer.removeProcessor(processor1);
                return true;
	}
	return false;
}
```

@santouits While that might be a valid solution for many users, for various reasons, I can't just return true for some of my InputProcessors. I could likely work around it with other solutions, but I wanted to see if there was a universally better option first.

Without any fix, the issue of adding additional processors to the front of an array causing input to be dropped would still exist. [The current fix removes this by adding an explicit exception on insert at position during iteration.](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/237201beb0c5fafad9cb4503105b78a12c5fc6a3/gdx/src/com/badlogic/gdx/utils/DelayedRemovalArray.java#L142)

Prefix example of dropped input:
```java
import com.badlogic.gdx.*;
import com.badlogic.gdx.backends.lwjgl.LwjglApplication;

public class InputMultiplexerAddTest extends ApplicationAdapter {
	InputMultiplexer multiplexer;
	InputTestProcessor processor1;
	InputTestProcessor processor2;
	InputTestProcessor processor3;
	
	@Override
	public void create () {
		multiplexer = new InputMultiplexer();

		processor1 = new InputTestProcessor();
		processor2 = new InputTestProcessor();
		processor3 = new InputTestProcessor();
		multiplexer.addProcessor(processor1);
		multiplexer.addProcessor(processor2);
		
		Gdx.input.setInputProcessor(multiplexer);
	}
	
	@Override
	public void render()
	{
		if(processor1.enterPressed || processor2.enterPressed || processor3.enterPressed)
			System.out.println(processor1.enterPressed + " " + processor2.enterPressed + " " + processor3.enterPressed);
		super.render();
	}

	public static void main (String[] args) throws Exception {
		new LwjglApplication(new InputMultiplexerAddTest());
	}
	
	class InputTestProcessor extends InputAdapter
	{
		private boolean enterPressed = false;
		@Override
		public boolean keyDown (int keycode) {
			if(keycode == Input.Keys.ENTER) {
				enterPressed = true;
			}
			return false;
		}
		
		@Override
		public boolean keyUp (int keycode) {
			if(keycode == Input.Keys.ENTER) {
				enterPressed = false;
				
				if(multiplexer.getProcessors().size < 3)
					multiplexer.addProcessor(0, processor3);
			}
			return false;
		}
	}
}
```

This example will cause processor2 to think enter is still pressed.
